@flexiarg structure/two-projections-of-one-quantity
@title Two Projections of One Quantity
@sigils [☀/影]
@keywords projection, latent quantity, duality, covariance, aliveness, mana, anamnesis, one-source, unification, shadow, intervene-at-the-source
@audience modellers, mission authors, theory-builders, anyone reconciling two measures that covary
@tone foundational
@style pattern

! conclusion: When two apparently-distinct quantities consistently covary or read as duals, model them as two PROJECTIONS of one underlying quantity — π₁(Q) and π₂(Q) — so their relationship becomes a structural fact about Q and its projection maps, not a coincidence to explain or a causal arrow to assert.

  + context: You hold two named observables — two metrics, two phenomena, two affects — that keep
    moving together, trading off, or appearing as opposite faces of the same thing. You are tempted
    to either (a) draw a causal arrow between them, or (b) shrug the covariance off as incidental.

  + IF:
      Two (or more) quantities A and B covary, trade off, or present as a duality across many
      instances, and you need a model that predicts their joint behaviour and tells you where to act.

  + HOWEVER:
      A causal arrow A→B (or B→A) usually over-fits — it breaks on the cases where they decouple, and
      it misnames the structure. Treating the covariance as coincidence is worse: it discards a real
      regularity and leaves you intervening on shadows. Neither "A causes B" nor "A and B are
      unrelated" is the right shape.

  + THEN:
      Posit a single latent quantity Q and two projection maps π₁, π₂ such that A = π₁(Q) and
      B = π₂(Q). Model Q and the projections explicitly. Read the A–B relationship off the geometry of
      (π₁, π₂): where the projections align, A and B covary; where they are orthogonal, A and B
      decouple — and that decoupling is now PREDICTED, not anomalous. Route interventions and
      predictions through Q: moving Q moves both projections coherently; acting on A alone is acting on
      a shadow.

  + BECAUSE:
      A shared latent source is the parsimonious explanation of covariance (one quantity, two shadows)
      and turns an apparent duality into structure: the two faces are guaranteed related because they
      are views of one thing, and guaranteed to decouple exactly where the projections diverge.
      Crucially it relocates agency — you intervene on Q (which the projections obey) instead of
      fighting one observable while the other springs back. The canonical instance: EOI, AIF surprise,
      anamnesis (un-discharged tension), the operator's T, Alexander's wholeness, and Salingaros'
      geometric tension are not six measures to reconcile pairwise but six projections of one
      *aliveness*-quantity — so mana flows when anamnesis discharges by construction, not by lucky
      correlation.

